@DoneHome Your example uses `time.sleep()`, which blocks the Twisted reactor loop.  What it's actually doing is starting an endless number of HTTP requests which will never complete since the reactor loop never gets any time to run and do the actual I/O.  Transformed into code which won't block the reactor:

```python
from twisted.python.task import react, deferLater

@inlineCallbacks
def request_done(resp):
       text = yield treq.content(resp)

@inlineCallbacks
 def main(reactor, *args):
         while True:
              yield deferLater(reactor, 0.01, lambda: None)
              d = treq.get('http://www.google.com')
              d.addCallback(request_done)

react(main, [])
```

This will make tons of concurrent requests and won't do anything useful, but it will only leak to the extent that the rate of request creation likely exceeds the rate at which they are completed.

(I can't close this ticket, but this isn't a treq bug.)

