Your example said that, in `Person.__init__`. :) This is  [by design](https://github.com/RDFLib/rdflib/blob/master/rdflib/resource.py#L272), to make the subclass work for all wrapped graph methods, in cases where a Resource subclass adds additional features that you want available on all returned resources (as illustrated in the doctest example linked above).

That evidently clashes with your usage, which ties subclasses to specific values for `rdf:type`. The solution is for you to override the `_new` method in your subclass:

    def _new(self, subject):
        return Resource(self._graph, subject)

... I leave selecting specific subclass based on `rdf:type` (and auto-registering this) as an exercise for the interested... ;)

