@denis-ryzhkov thanks for the investigation! You're right, the issues seems to be that the auto naming of the Enum field that a Django choice field gets converted to is likely to clash with an existing type in your schema since it's just the object type name plus the field name: https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene-django/blob/a480a39713d3392dc3a7cee9565989a713d05856/graphene_django/converter.py#L50

I think the fix for that is make the generated name more explicit and less likely to clash with anything in the schema. Something like `DjangoModel{object_name}{field_name}Choices` (e.g. `DjangoModelFooTypeChoices`).

Separately, disabling the conversion of Django choice fields to Enums is a good idea since it's not always desired. Though I think it's probably something that should be done on a field level rather than globally.

Ah, thanks for clarifying. A minimal example is that `a|b\n-|-\nc|d` is parsed as a table but `a|b\n\0-|-\nc|d` is not.

This explains where the Markdown module isn't behaving as you expected. But the behavior of the Markdown module makes sense: `\0--- | ---` is not a row specification, so this shouldn't be parsed as a table. The root cause comes earlier: why does the string that you're trying to use as a table have NUL characters in it?

First: what is the rank of string tensor that you're passing to `tf.summary.text`? (Or, rather, what is the lowest rank for which you're able to reproduce surprising behavior?)

Now, consider the following statements:
  - the contents of the string tensor that you're passing to `tf.summary.text` contains NUL characters;
  - the event files on disk contain NUL characters within your text;
  - the protobufs read into memory by TensorBoard's event accumulator contain NUL characters;
  - the tensor protos returned by `self._multiplexer.Tensors` in the text plugin contain NUL characters;
  - the result of `tf.make_ndarray(event.tensor_proto)` contains NUL characters;
  - any argument to `markdown_and_sanitize` contains NUL characters.

As far as I can tell, the above statements *should* all be equivalent, and furthermore if they are all equivalent then TensorBoard's behavior is correct.

