```

Just to add another option to that, you can also use `None` as a default argument (or something else, if you want to enable pointers); in the called function, if that arg is `None`, then simply construct what you want.
If you want to make sugar, you could do something like this (though this is for an extremely simple case):
```
auto bind_with_lazy_default(auto& scope, const string& name, auto&& func, auto&& default_func) {
  scope.def(name.c_str(), [](py::object obj) {
    ArgType arg;
    if (obj.is_none()) {
      arg = default_func();
    } else {
      arg = py::cast<ArgType>(obj);
    }
    return func(arg);
  });
}
```
(Above is psuedo-code, you'll have to do quite a bit more to generalize it).

That being said, jagerman's second option, registering two overloads, is probably by far the simplest.

